commentText: If you liked this watch the Martian, it's another believable and tense space film :D

Her panic and suffocation made my heart beat hard and relive what happened to me almost 10 years ago: awake paralysis and suffocation during an operation in Brighton in 2005. First the hospital/anaesthetists said nothing went wrong. Then the consultant anaesthetist (my call to him in desperation) said it was 'awareness' (meaning what's usually called anaesthetic awareness in the UK or unintended intra-operative awareness in the USA). Then this same man at the end of a farcical meeting said I had experienced 'emergence phenomenon' - but decided not to tell me what that was. Then in response to my letter of complaint the Chief exec wrote that nothing went wrong and didn't use any name for what had occurred - supposedly just my abnormal response to normal events. They contacted my GP and told him something but I asked him and he refused to tell me what he had been told. He said at one point 'they didn't know what went wrong' - but of course they must have = a lie. You'd think (with all their expensive legal expertise paid for by clients/users of their services = us) they'd have created and stuck to one coherent and consistent story wouldn't you? Yup: suffocation is a terrible way to die and many of us will die in this way. It is utter HELL. I survived it but others have died and will die in hospital because of medical errors by anaesthetists, surgeons, operating department practitioners (ODPs), nurses, recovery room staff etc. A weekend so no senior staff on-site, agency nurses, poor training for all concerned, arrogance, incompetence, misdiagnosis,not listened to or believed (before and after)... Can't fix it after (nor my injuries) so it's GOT to be prevention: 'saving' money kills and destroys lives and costs far more in the longterm - but only IF our and our friends' families' lives and health are given their correct value.

+Vignesh Sundaram Wait... this was "flawless"? Right off the bat they get things so utterly wrong it's shameful. The ISS/Hubble are in low Earth orbit and mere hundreds of miles from Earth -- comms and GPS satellites are tens of thousands of miles out in space. There is no way a comms sat, or its orbiting debris, would cross paths with the ISS or Hubble, much less within moments of its destruction. It would take many hours (up to twenty) if the debris headed straight for Earth, which it likely wouldn't. The whole "chain reaction" scenario is also abject bullshit. Satellites aren't lined up in a single orbit distance and also not on a single path like dominoes. And even worse, they play into the ridiculous and patently unrealistic cool, chilled out male saves helpless woman bullshit. It's about time we left that tripe behind in the Edwardian/Victorian Era stories where it belonged. NASA's own studies on Mars mission simulations, as well as those conducted by the Chinese and the Europeans, all demonstrated that women do much better in extremely stressful situations than men. Yeah, it's Hollywood and an obviously fictional story, but ffs... It was painful as fuck as an educated person to watch that bullshit.

commentText: People comparing Gravity to Interstellar are missing the point entirely. Quite literally an apples-to-oranges comparison fallacy. Just because the two movies are sci fi (and Gravity really is not true SF since it doesn't imagine any technology we don't already have), doesn't make them remotely similar. Interstellar is a relatively sedate "big-story" sci fi epic. Gravity is an intimate character portrait coupled with an action-adventure thriller. Two very different kinds of movie. Thinking they are somehow comparable, just because both are set in space, is naive. They're both excellent movies that are very effective at achieving their very different goals. Interstellar's goal is to make you think. Gravity's goal is to make you care.

People keep comparing this to Interstellar but these two films are kind of different. There is a different premise for both films. Try and remember this. The only similarity of both these films is the setting, which is space. And that is all. Gravity, a lady who is trying to return to earth. Interstellar, people that are trying to leave earth. Can't you see? Over all, for a film, I would like to watch what is entertaining, and of that I choose Interstellar. Interesting plot, interesting premise, character development, more emotional instances. If I would like to watch a more down to earth film, which bases more on plot situation more that any other element, then its Gravity. And if you notice, the film is in real-time. Everything happens in almost 90 minutes or so. The film is also more believable and laid back. You just watch what happens. For Interstellar, you have to think in order to get the gist of the movie, and it looks like a handful of people were having trouble with that. But Gravity is missing the awe, the "what if" and imagination, stepping out the comfort zone. So the aim of both films are different. But I'll say this. The film that left me thinking for days after watching it was Interstellar. That's gotta mean something, right?

I think there are a lot of points to take into consideration , when discussing gravity , not only because it is one of the most highly rated movies of all time , but because it has created such a big division not only among science fiction fanatics but among movie goers in general . Let us get one thing straight . Gravity is a good movie , Is it the best sci_fi I have ever seen ? Absolutely not . did it break the mould ? yeah somehow , but not necessarily because of its presentation or ideas , but more because most of the sci_fi people watch nowadays are so mainstream they mostly worship action , cliches and aliens . gravity in all its essence is really a very simple story about survival . something more akin to cast away than star wars . If gravity was a book , then it would be a short story , not a novel . Back story that is so important in character arcs is not fully exposed on purpose (they could have used flashbacks for example but they didn't) , all you need to know about sandra bullock 's character is that her daughter died , and that she has been living in sorrow ever since .They never fully explored the main character for a few reasons . This is my interpertation of course : Firstly they wanted you to be fully invested in the setting as much as possible , and secondly maybe they thought it would be a tad melodramatic and cliched . Visually speaking , the film is stunning , that every scene so painstakingly crafted is a story in its own . Gravity is not only a simple story favouring symbolism over conventional storytelling but also a visual experience that makes up for its lack of dialogue through prestine , thought provoking imagery that will haunt your dreams for how lonely and dark space can be , yet so beautiful and endless that it would take your breath away . That is why it is so crafty , a single frame can make up for thousands of lines . That is why so many adore this movie . My brother who is a very hard to please kind of person thought it a perfect movie and gave it a 10 . It depends really on your kind of personality . He saw in its simplicity and hauntingly beautiful imagery a story in its own . He loved clooney 's nobelity and liked bulock's fight for survival . But that didn't make it the best movie i ever saw . Yeah the visuals enhanced the atmosphere dramatically and yeah I liked clooney's character . I just never felt for sandra bullock's character . Maybe I demanded more backstory , maybe the role needed a lesser known actress , I just don't know . Visual imagery was indeed striking but iam one of those people that far favors emotional investment in my stories over gorgeous visual imagery . Simple strorytelling is a double edged sword in movies , and lack in character backstory would have been forgiven if i was emotionaly invested in the fight or if the premise was more original , but neither was the case . But as i said before , gravity is more than the sum of its parts , and I try to understand as much as i can, why people like it so much . It is just that I can't totally adore it or see it as a flawless movie as other people do .

I have seen a great number of Science Fiction films over the years and read a great many novels. I did not see this in the theater because I knew the scenes would make me dizzy and uncomfortable. I just watched it last night on a large screen TV, and it was over hyped, over rated and no way deserved Oscars except for the SFX. Just as many had observed when it was released it had no plot, no character development, lots of impossible events to swallow, but it was also BORING as hell when there was no explosions or fast flying astronauts to watch, Bullock fiddling with buttons and trying to grab onto parts of the satellites put me to sleep. In the Sci-Fi and Horror genres you have to be able to suspend disbelief when it comes to storyline, you mean to tell me that Dr. Bullock was able to get into a Chinese spacecraft and go 'eny, meny, miny, moe' and pick the right buttons to push to land her safely in the water of earth? 2001 A Space Odyssey it is not, which is why it is being quickly forgotten. Another example of special effects over story and performance. Cloney was the stereotyped tragic hero, and had to do the 'let me die to save you' cliche, Sandra was nominated for an Oscar for going 'uhhh, oh, help, need air, uh, oh, ah' for an hour'?

I have not seen Interstellar, but I heard it was a good movie. I watched this one and it was literally the worst movie I've seen in years. I can't even think of anything to compare it to. It had good special effects though, but that's where the good news stops.

Interstellar has a smarter plot, and will do a good job of making you think about it after you watch it. Gravity is a more emotionally intense movie, and will do a good job of making you feel like you're floating in space. Both films are visually and musically spectacular. I personally enjoyed Gravity's musical score and art direction more, and Interstellar's plot more. The science of Interstellar is a mix of real physics, alongside some speculative physics, particularly toward the end. The drought on Earth is also unrealistic. However, the astral physics is done superbly: you get to see what a black hole actually looks like, what a wormhole would look like, the time dilation effects, etc. Some of the individual frames were calculated by a supercomputer running for days long, and the results were used in two academic papers. Interstellar's plot is extremely convoluted, almost paradoxical, but it all technically fits with no inconsistencies if you think about it, and if you buy the speculative plot devices. However, I did not buy Interstellar emotionally. Much of the characterization seemed forced and some of the character personalities were inconsistently developed. Many people will disagree with me on this. The emotional scenes were hit and miss for me, but drama is more subjective. Gravity's physics tries to be as realistic as possible, but they got some things wrong. For example, the satellites are going round the Earth in the wrong direction. However, most of the floating around is very well done; Buzz Aldrin said it looked pretty much like how it actually looked when they were floating in the vessel. The main conflict is a problem that could actually happen in real life, but they ignore the fact that satellites travel at different relative speeds, making most of the plot technically impossible. Gravity's plot is straightforward but relies on incredible coincidences, which could shake your suspension of disbelief. However, this does not mean Gravity is a "stupid" film. Many scenes have nice artistic touches, obvious symbolism, etc. The music is very inventive and designed to replace sound because there's no sound in space. The direction is also top-notch, and makes you feel stranded in space. It is a beautiful film. Overall, Interstellar is the better film if you want to think, be puzzled, and have your imagination stirred, in the classic science fiction sense. Gravity is the better film if you want to have an emotionally gripping artistic "experience" of space. They are both amazing films. I usually go for complex plots and films that make me think, but in this case Gravity moved me more, I was disoriented and on the edge of my seat through most of it. The two films compliment each other.

From the positive reviews of this movie I expected something well researched, deep and subtle. In the end it was just another flashy American movie made for people with short attention spans and a lack of critical thinking skills. If you know anything about satellites, orbits and space debris you might find it difficult to suspend your disbelief. How likely is it that debris from one destroyed satellite hits the Hubble space telescope, the ISS, several other satellites and a Chinese space station too? Multiple times, over multiple passes. This movie goes from one suspenseful moment to another, to another, to another, to another and to yet another. After awhile I found myself rolling my eyes every time something went wrong. The suspense was fake and manufactured, I can only pretend to be genuinely concerned for the main character's life so many times before I get desensitized, because who am I kidding, she's not going to die, that'd compromise the feel good moment at the end when she feels reborn and happy to be alive! Can't have that. Having said that, this movie did genuinely have me tearing up in the quiet moments between the flashy special effects and explosions, only to pull me right back out of the movie again with another moment I'm expected to get all tense over again. Dialogue is a bit corny too, but I'm not really a person who cares so much about that. I'd probably give it a 3 or 4 out of 10. If you're not too critical of movies and like allot of suspense in your films, then you'll probably really like this, because in essence it's not a bad film, it's just cheap and pandering, which some people are into.

Thought experiment: How a man can traverse space in all directions, even back and forth from distant points, without the need for jet propulsion. Imagine a man floating in space. He does not have any type of propulsion system such as a jet-pack or boosters. He has an umbrella made of Kevlar which is spread open and tethered to his waistline. The tether is several meters in length, is strength rated for towing, and is fully extended so that a tug on the umbrella will in turn be kinetically transferred to the man, via the tether. The man has a wrist rocket sling shot strapped to his forearm and wrist that is in prime position for firing. He has attached to his chest a pouch full of lead ball weights, each weighing about 3 ounces. The man loads a lead ball into the sling shot and fires it at near full capacity into the concave side of umbrella (now you know why the umbrella is made of Kevlar ;). The momentum of the travelling lead ball is transferred into the umbrella and the umbrella moves slightly in the same direction the ball had been travelling, thereby causing the man to move in the same direction as well. As he fires one shot after another into the umbrella, the speed at which he traverses space increases with each shot. When the man runs out lead balls to fire from his sling shot, he reels in the umbrella- which now retains the entire contents of his ammunition pouch. After retrieving all of the ammunition from the umbrella and placing each ball back into the ammunition pouch attached to his chest, he can now push the umbrella away from him in any direction he chooses, and can again begin the process of his sling shot powered propulsion system.

Space Odyssey - yeah, it's sci-fi but idea itself was similar and no wonder it's classic. This one didn't have that feeling, there you felt such a stranger in a world in which you have little chances to stay alive. For example, why there was so much sound in space? Scenes in space should have been in silence, just with people talking. Why did Sandra's character was counting on luck then she was pushing buttons in chinese station? I know she was on stress but they showed her as if she counted on luck with that mini miny mo bs rather using logic. All in all she supposed to be professional and have some basic psychological training to avoid "mini miny mo" as a way to stay alive. Oh, and I loved how she was hanging on that station before entering. Trailer showed explosions and action, so it isn't surprise that people expected more action, explosions in actual movie. And overall those moments then she was alone was boring. There was almost no narrative, only doing actions. Basically we don't learn too much about her character. Yeah, the situation was you had too save your ass, not remembering great moments of your life, but there was a way to show those things. For example it could be done while she was talking with Chinese man in chinese station. It's like they tried to mix action with psychological moments. No wonder it lasted less than 90 minutes. Not saying that movie is bad but it was overrated. With more character development, without hurry to start tragedy happening, trying to focus on that things rather showing her superhero-like abilities while hanging on flying station while avoiding debris, with less sound in space, it would be much better, it doesn't matter it had some great moments.

Creating the 3D in Gravity. Gravity, the highly-acclaimed, intensely emotional space thriller, has been hailed as some of the - if not the VERY - best 3D footage ever seen on the big screen. This has led to some surprise when learning that Gravity was NOT shot in 3D. However, it wasn't entirely converted in post either. It featured an innovative and unique workflow that incorporated 3D conversion during production as well as a complex integration with 3D VFX. In a conversation with Prime Focus World, we find out how they did it.
Wonderful special effects - pity they were wasted on a dumb, flippantly formulaic script.

It turned out that they paid millions in the making of this movie but couldn't spend 100 $ for a physiscs student to tell them how the physics of space work. There are many, many things that can go wrong in space. Actually, just one tiny part of a former satelite can destroy an entire space station if you have bad luck. But they had to come up with this debris-cloud shit which expands within 2 hours to a size that cannot be avoided. Nearly everything in this movie is just wrong. Really, really wrong. There are at least 10 big mistakes, just to name a few: Logic fails: - Scientific personell are not instructed how to operate shuttles or pods. That's what pilots are for. - Even if they would be instructed, if you know how to fly an American pod/shuttle doesn't mean you can do so with a Russian/Chinese one WITHOUT TRAINING. - There is EXACTLY the amount of escape pods needed to evacuate the personell on a space station. Not even ONE SEAT MORE. Why should there be a reserve pod? Bringing thing up into space is expensive. - She is trained how to fly a capsule but she is not trained that if you land in water you have to get rid of your space suite before you leave your craft? That is something scientific personell actually IS instructed in. - Underwear. Sorry Sandra, you don't wear sexy underwear in space, you wear diapers and many wrappers of ugly stuff. - Hubble and ISS are on completely different orbits and by far not in the line of sight of each other (except you can see 100mi+ in the BEST case, meaning when the orbits are closest) - Bullock plays a medical doctor. What the fuck is she doing with Hubble? - ... Physics fails (which is nearly everything, but I'll give you some): - Kessler syndrome is pictured wrong. Though it is true that collisions between space debris creates bigger clouds of smaller debris which will most likely cause problems for space traveling in the future and already has partially, this is a process that takes more than a few minutes (for some satelites this will be months to years or even decades). It is very unlikely for objects in space to hit each other, even in fixed orbits, space is HUGE. The movie states this can happen within minutes. - If there would be satelites in the same orbit (height) as the ISS they would have the EXACT same speed as the ISS. If an object gains speed in the direction it is flying into it gains height, meaning it will go to a higher orbit. - You can see the debris field flying towards the ISS and it is pretty slow. The ISS has an orbital speed of 28000 km/h. A debris field on the same orbit would have the EXACT same speed as the ISS. However, if the debris field would have a different inclination AND the same orbital height and speed it CAN be possible that they cross their path after ~93 minutes (the time the ISS takes to fly around the earth once). But there are a lot of calculations needed to rendezvous with an orbital object in space, there is NO WAY a random debris field hits the same object twice. However, if there were 2 objects on same orbits with different inclination having a rendezvous the colision speed would be pretty high (and by pretty high I mean several times the speed of sound). - Communication satelites are on much, much higher orbits than the ISS (meaning 100x higher). There is NO WAY a debris field in the orbit of the ISS can ever hit a satelite that far away within such a short amount of time and take all satelites out. This is ridiculously stupid. - BTW orbits: The satelite debris flies into the wrong direction (satelites fly west to east, not east to west). - Even if this would happen, communication between Earth and the ISS doesn't rely on satelites only, so even if all satelites in space would disappear all of a sudden you would still be able to have radio contact to Earth. - The rope scene where Clooney plays the hero: My brain hurt. It seems Newtons first law doesn't apply in space. Wrong. It does. So after the rope was stretched they would've bounced back towards the ISS (not to mention the stupidity of the rest of the whole scene like when Bullock opens the outter airlock it would have smashed her to nirvana). - Why is the Chinese space station falling towards earth again? And if so, how for fucks sake could Bullock be in the reach of it? Remember orbits and speeds? - The teardrop is bullshit. Even if you haven't got the $100 to ask a physics student you could at least have watched some of Chris Hadfield's explanations on Youtube. - ... That's about the things they got wrong. On an emotional level thought, this movie... still sucks. "... be able to watch and understand this movie deeply ..." It's about not giving in even if you are close to losing your will to fight for your life, got that. Pretty emotional, huh? Too bad Bullock is a very bad actress for roles like that and the scenario didn't get me (I may have been influenced by the huge amount of physical and logical bullshit going on, who knows?). There are a lot of movies that get the emotional part for losing your will to live and the "fight for your life against nature"-stuff better, e.g. The Grey, Into The Wild, 127 Hours and so on. And they are all more credible (damn, Liam Neeson fights a CGI wolf and I still find it more emotional). What was left of the movie for me was a huge CGI-orgy and personally I don't like CGI-orgies. But that's just a matter of opinion. For me, given the stupid story and the bad acting, Gravity is on the same level as Transformers just with less cool robots. Is that enough of an explanation? :D

commentText: I love anything that involves astronomy and stuff like that, but this has to be the most dramatic movie that I've ever heard of so, i'm not even going to think of watching this shit.

Warning: this is an attempt to express my views on the movie. OPINIONS AHEAD! "Meh. It was aight." But seriously, I enjoyed Gravity to an extent. The action scenes were amazing and. . . well. . . that's about it. The cast was a poor choice. Watching Bullock ,(A trained astronaut.), fret for for her life like she did was just dumb. For ANYONE to be qualified to go on a spacewalk, ESPECIALLY to service the Hubble, that person would have had to go through months of training and preparation. Not only training for when it goes right, but when it goes wrong. In fact, a large portion of Astronaut training exercises focus on situations that go wrong, to prepare the astronaut for a dangerous mission. A mission, might I add, you wouldn't be chatting it up during. "WHAT DO I DO WHAT DO I DO?!" is a statement you should NEVER hear from an astronaut, and especially not a space-walker. And I shouldn't even mention the useless "Oh you're running out of air" mechanic that served no purpose. After telling her to breathe lightly, Clooney then proceeds to ask her about her life back on Earth. I call BS. I wouldn't have had a problem in a more Science-fiction movie, but this entire flick is meant to actually happen. And it can. And if they wanted to be accurate, they sure didn't do a good job. I don't feel like pointing out all of the movies flaws. But I must re-state: I did not hate this movie. I just think it was a simple "cash-in" on space to the general audience. The praise this movie is getting is(in my opinion) not deserved. I'm seeing this movie being put on number 1 spots on top 10 Space movies, or some other countdown. The word "Brilliant" is a VERY generous compliment to Gravity. Not to say that it sucked the big one, but definitely not the top of its class. If people are impressed and "deeply moved" by this movie, they are most likely new to the genre. Go watch 2001: A Space Odyssey. LOADS better.

So glad im not the only one who thought this movie was garbage! just another 90 minutes of "avatar" like 3D CGI nonsense with next to no research gone into space travel, physics etc. Thanks to IMDB user "nysalesman" for the review! "1) Bullock is nauseous during a space walk. This would never happen. It is only during space walks that space sickness can kill, because vomiting in your enclosed suit would cause you to inhale and choke on the vomit. It is for this reason that food is not consumed for hours prior to an EVA (Extra Vehicular Activity) and astronauts are required to abort the walk when there's even a hint of nausea 2) Bullock is untethered,spinning and flailing in space. This is highly unlikely. NASA procedure is to always have an emergency MMU called a SAFER during EVA. The pack is programmed to automatically adjust yaw, roll, and pitch to stop the astronaut from spinning. Routine procedure is then to manually take control of the jetpack and use it to return to the space vehicle 3) The Soyez TMA re-entry module requires an EVA to disengage the chute. Correct me if I'm wrong, but it is my understanding that this model would allow the astronaut to disengage the chute from within the capsule. BTW, if the chute did deploy, it wouldn't have been opened up and spread all over the station. The parachute compartment hatch would have simply been blown off and the parachute would have remained packed away in the module - there is no wind in space 4) The opening line states that there is no sound in space. However, we hear the wrench actuating when used by Sandra Bullock 5) George Clooney has Bullock on a long tether to distance her from the jets on his jetpack. However, he's holding on to her in front of himself, where she is just as clear of them as he is. Also, the propellent is inert gas, so it would not have hurt her. BTW, Clooney later drifts into space when there is no discernible force to push him away from Bullock 6) The re-entry capsules have a hard 60-second count down before undocking. No way. Design of space vehicles offer manual over-rides for nearly everything. If there were a count down, then there would be an over-ride as well 7) One exploding satellite would not cause a chain reaction of debris. It's called space for a reason, there is a lot of it. Debris from one satellite is highly unlikely to cause further debris 8) Every satellite and space station is bombarded by the debris as if they are all in the same orbit. They are not. For that matter, neither is the Hubble and ISS 9) When Bullock takes off her space suit, there is no liquid cooled ventilation unit, catheter, or diaper: which are required attire for EVA 10) Bullock stabilizes and orients the proper re-entry path of the re-entry module from a spin while well beyond the window for a deorbit burn 11) No way someone with the emotional baggage of Bullock's character would ever be chosen for a space mission 12) Bullock went through astronaut training and wasn't taught to brace herself when using a propellent in zero G 13) The hatch on the Soyez reentry module is much higher and would not have flooded so easily. Additionally, the Soyez, while being designed to land on solid ground, is also designed with floatation devices for water landing and does not have explosive bolts on the hatch. So it would not have flooded like Grissom's Liberty Bell 7"

replies.commentText: Tell me scientist.What is so unrealistic about the cloud of debris that knows nothing about the laws of physics?

+TrkJustin Count, my ignorant friend: 1. Space stations, telescopes and communication satellites do not orbit the planet on a narrow circular orbit 100 meters wide. One destroyed satellite physically cannot destroy half of man-made objects in orbit. 2. Assuming that exploded satellite was in motion, so its debris will also be in motion. After each subsequent collision they will lose momentum and kinetic energy, which means they will randomly change direction and slow down. 3. The cloud definitely possessed an advanced AI, since it was picking its targets very accurately. On several occasions it precisely destroyed the shuttle crew and ISS, but all debris all the time missed Bullock herself even when she was in outer space near the aforementioned ISS.

The film's cascade of debris is a very real possibility. This scenario is known as the Kessler syndrome, named after N.A.S.A. scientist Donald J. Kessler who first proposed the theory in 1978. A cascading Kessler syndrome involving an object the size of the International Space Station would trigger a catastrophic chain-reaction of debris. The orbiting debris field would make it impossible to launch space exploration missions or satellites for many decades
Just to clear this up for you IDIOT

+Jason Matthew I thought that my reply was in English, but looks like some people have problems understanding plain English. Ok, let me spell it out for you, Jason (I'll capitalize the most crucial parts so that you don't miss them). And a little piece of advice for the future - before posting quotes from wikipedia with a smart look on your face at least do SOME READING on the subject. 1. All space objects shown to form the cloud in the movie are located on different altitudes and have different orbit inclines (which I already mentioned here). Astophysicists who analyzed the movie pointed out that all those objects COULDN'T BE DESTROYED in a chain reaction (unless explosions happen on all altitudes simultaneously, which is not the case in the movie). 2. If you bothered to spend some time reading about Kessler syndrome, you would know that its depiction in the movie in UNREALISTIC and DOES NOT CORRESPOND TO REAL LAWS OF PHYSICS. The event itself is possible, but a significant density of artificial objects is required for that and it will take decades to accumulate debris, not 15 minutes. If you're looking for a realistic depiction of space works (including the theme of space debris) in near future, "Planetes" would be a good choice.

Plus let's assume Russia would be dumb enough to use a missile to deorbit(?) a satellite. That's pretty dumb in itself. Also let's assume all comms sats are all snuggling together at those orbits. I know this is a long post, but I feel the need to write it: I feel compelled to post this message in response to the various amount of hate that Gravity seems to be receiving at the moment, especially on this comment section. I will stress now that for those of you who didn't like this film, I have no problem with that whatsoever! We all have different tastes and film is subjective at the end of the day. There are going to be films that many people like that you don't and vice versa. We all have different perspectives when it comes to films, so I think it's wrong for people to call you idiots or whatever. For me personally, I loved Gravity. I saw it in the cinema last November and I loved it. I bought the Blu-Ray yesterday, watched it last night, I loved it. It's my favourite film of 2013. Why do I love it you may ask? Well, first and foremost, it was because of the experience of being in outer space. Gravity is very much an experience film. A film that you're supposed to immerse yourself in and go in for the ride. On that basis, Gravity delivered that aspect for me. The direction, visuals, music and even the physics portrayed in this film helped that tremendously in my opinion. Just watching the visuals and seeing Sandra Bullock's character overcome the odds stacked against her was intense and absorbing. Because I felt like I was in space with her, I felt her emotions, I felt her loneliness, I felt her need to survive. Also, the end sequence? It gives me chills every time. It is an amazing sequence with the visuals and especially the music. It's a film that's not so much to be watched as it is to be felt and it's also a survival film. What annoys me about the reaction to this film is how many people just look for the bad things in it and they totally disregard the good stuff. Do we look at all the individual moments we hate or dislike in a film, or do we look at the bigger picture? I think it makes more sense to balance out the good and the bad of a film and see which one holds up more, instead of just focusing on the bad. One of the complaints people give is that it has no story. I disagree. It is a basic story, but it's still a story! A story about a person in space trying to get back to earth after a disaster takes place. After all, it is a survival film. There's only so much you can do with a premise about a person trying to survive a disaster or an event that arises. I mean, what were people expecting with a film like this? Considering the basic material Alfonson Cuaron had to work with, I thought he did a great job! The film also deals with issues like loneliness, despair, isolation, spirituality, etc, so there's more to this film than people give credit for. I've never seen a survival film done this way before, so Cuaron covered new ground with this film in my opinion. In terms of the physics, dialogue and cliches in this film? There were maybe a couple of problems, but they never really bothered me that much. It's in my top ten favourite films of all time and I don't care if people think I'm overrating the film or that I don't have a good taste. I loved the film and nobody will change my enjoyment of this film! At the end of the day though, if people don't like it because they found it boring or they couldn't get into it, that's totally fine. We all have different opinions and it's a shame that a fair amount of people don't like it, but I wish people wouldn't be as harsh on this film and at least consider the good aspects to it and I believe you can find many. Some people who call it the worst film ever made are just being WAY too critical in my opinion. If you think I have a bad taste in films, here are my top ten favourite films of all time so you can be the judge: 10. Groundhog Day 9. Inception 8. Itâ€™s a Wonderful Life 7. Brazil 6. Gravity 5. The Lord of the Rings Trilogy 4. The Elephant Man 3. Fantasia 2. Vertigo 1. 2001: A Space Odyssey I wanted to post this message because I feel that, while people are not wrong for disliking this film, I do believe some people are being a bit too harsh on it in my humble opinion. I mean, why do some people feel the need to be so aggressively negative towards to it? It's just a film at the end of the day. Don't get so worked up over it! and secondly, I wanted to let some of you guys know why me and many others loved this film.

SPOILER ALERT!! As much effort as they put in portraying zero-g physics as accurately as possible, there is a MAJOR error which I can't forgive the film, namely when George Clooney's character dies. I mean, they were at a stand-still, therefore if Sandra Bullock let go, they should have remained stationary. What invisible force was propelling Clooney away? I don't mind a few difficult to believe things, like the fire-extinguisher scene, but this is over the line, and it's not worth it for the sake of drama in a movie like this, IMO. Otherwise great movie.

replies.commentText: You are ensuring there was a major mistake as if you were an astrophysicist. I don't think they would commit that type of mistake. I'm not an expert but i don't think they where at a stand-still force point.

+kiljaeden2222 Obviously I'm not an astrophysicist, but if you check the movie again, they ARE at a stand-still. Sandra Bullock has a rope on her leg, and it's stretched out and it stopped both of them. By the laws of physics even the movie has established until that point, Clooney should not fly away upon letting go of the rope. I doubt is was windy up there, so they could have killed him off in a more believable way, cos as it is, that one scene damages the quality of the otherwise truly awesome movie.
Not to mention, even if he did receive a little force as he left the craft, he'd be back in a few hours as the orbit went all the way around.

I went in prepared to love the movie, but I just didn't care at all what happened to the characters; no decent dialogue, no character development, and a very standard plot structure. The visuals were cool BUT this movie was rife with physical inaccuracies...which really pissed me off because I have a pretty deep understanding of physics. Namely, the scene where George Clooney had to let go - there was no force pulling him away from Sandra Ball-sac to begin with! No gravity, no centripital force. There wouldn't have been any tension on the tether that was holding them. They could have both let go and not moved an inch! Plus the orbits of the ISS, Hubble, and the Chinese station are so different, there's absolutely no way in hell a NASA jet pack (which was decommissioned years ago) could have gotten two astronauts from one to the other! Not to mention...why was Sandra Ball-sac up there in the first place?! She was wildly under-qualified and wasn't doing anything that an astronaut couldn't do!

replies.commentText: "When Kowalski unclips his tether and floats away to his death to save Stone from being pulled away from the ISS, several observers (including Plait and Tyson) contend that all Stone had to do was to give the tether a gentle tug, and Kowalski would have been safely pulled toward her, since the movie shows the pair having stopped and there would thus be no centrifugal force to pull Kowalski away." "Others, however, such as Kevin Grazier, science adviser for the movie, and NASA engineer Robert Frost, maintain that the pair are actually still decelerating, with Stone's leg caught in the parachute cords from the Soyuz. As the cords absorb her kinetic energy, they stretch. Kowalski's interpretation of the situation is that the cords are not strong enough to absorb his kinetic energy as well as hers, and that he must therefore release the tether to give her a chance of stopping before the cords fail and doom both of them" Wikipedia.

If you watch the scene again, you can clearly see on the left side of the screen that the parachute and cord were still slowly coming undone, they were not stopped fully. From the perspective of the character Kowalski who was in a life and death situation where you can't second guess your decisions, he did not want to risk Stone's life when she still had a chance. Kowalski was your "right stuff" kind of Astronaut like that. So he made his decision, and Stone lives. From the perspective of a movie-goer, I didn't think the movie was "full" of unrealistic BS, quite the opposite as a matter of fact. It focused on a lot of little details that most people didn't realize could happen in space. An example being the fire on board the station.

I practically predicted everything that these guys did horrifically wrong: 1) Matt (George Clooney) would have lived, if he weren't a cocky son of a bitch, that wanted to break that stupid "longest space walk" record, and if he didn't waste his fuel by flying laps around the space shuttle. 2) When you hear that space debris is coming your way, you drop everything IMMEDIATELY! 3) NASA could have predicted that there might be a debris chain reaction and would have called the mission off earlier. (also someone pointed out, that such a chain reaction is actually impossible) 4) I don't buy for a second that NASA couldn't establish ANY communication with the astronauts for the rest of the movie. A fucking Chinese bloke with a radio on Earth managed to contact Ryan (Sandra Bullock) in the Soyuz pod. 5) Ryan couldn't detach a harness that is made to be easy to handle. She stayed there like 2 minutes before detaching. 6) Any astronaut knows that oxygen is in short supply in space, and won't fucking have a panic attack every 5 minutes. An astronaut is trained to control their breathing. 7) Continuing the oxygen issue, you don't talk non-stop in space. Talking uses up more air. Matt knew Ryan had her tank low, yet he insisted she talked back to him. 8) These damn astronauts can't grab hold of anything if their life depended on it. Literally. Also those damn tethers break too easily. 9) There is a possibility that Matt could have lived if they both pulled fast and hard on that stupid tether. He would have definitely lived if he wasn't a cocky bastard earlier (see 1.) 10) Ryan takes a nice space stroll through the ISS (knowing full well that she is in danger). While doing this she didn't notice (or pay attention to) the electrical fire that was just starting. Also the fire alarm didn't detect fire, it only detected a fucking inferno. Fire is the most dangerous thing in space because oxygen saturation is a lot higher. Also without gravity, it's harder to control and it spreads faster. The fire detectors should detect a light candle, not wait till an out of control fire. 11) Ryan spend too much time on the intercom, trying to reach Matt or NASA, when it was already establish that Houston hasn't paid their phone bill. 12) Ryan doesn't know to brace herself before attempting to use a fire extinguisher in space. (At least she learned the hard way, and will use it properly later on). 13) NASA couldn't patch the software of the Soyuz to be able to use other languages (besides Russian) if necessary. It's the International Space Station. The only escape pods available should use a more international language. (i.e. English) 14) Ryan isn't careful enough with her tools. She almost lost that screwdriver while detaching the parachute off the Soyuz. 15) Ryan might be mentally challenged. She started howling like a wolf, to a Chinese bloke, instead of trying to save her ass. Also she is clearly depressed with suicidal tendencies. She probably wouldn't have gotten an OK from NASA. (Also hallucinating. But that could be because of the lack of oxygen). 16) Earlier Ryan proved she could stabilize the Soyuz pod, but when the Chinese Shenzou spirals out of control she does nothing. Autopilots are good, but that pod probably would have burned on re-entry in real life. 17) Ryan didn't try to respond to NASA before exiting the pod. Also she should have taken the uniform off before exiting the pod. Or she could have tried keeping her helmet on. No smoke to get in her suit, she could have just waited there for the rescue. (unless the pod caught fire. In that case she would have bailed out). So Hollywood, congrats on disappointing yet again.

replies.commentText: That wasn't a "Chinese bloke" on the radio. It was a Greenland native. How's that for nit-picking bullshit. So Alex Barbu, congrats on disappointing me.

+tigerburn81 Yeah... sorry but I don't care that much if I disappoint you. I'm not the one making big budget movies, with big name actors. Hollywood is. And Hollywood is screwing things up a lot lately. Maybe I did nitpick, but this was supposed to be a realistic situation. If the movie was about some astronauts colonizing Mars or Pandora or something, I would have probably let it slide. Just as I don't nitpick on Iron Man, because it isn't supposed to be realistic. Gravity, on the other hand, was supposed to portray realistically, what could happen to astronauts lost in space. The story is set in our time, in our universe. Not in the future, nor in some other imagined universe (Iron Man, Avengers, etc).

This movie was the biggest disappoint I've ever watched, and I didn't even have high expectations. Worse than Prometheus, worse than Avatar, on par with Elysium. I'm a big astrophysics fan and I work in a hospital lab; I was hooked about 10 minutes in. Then this film crashed and burned harder than the space station. Honestly, the CG and suspense was above average (I enjoyed it), but everything else was just brutal. The acting was mediocre at best; characters are all one-dimensional. The theme had much more potential. I cannot understand how people seriously think this movie is great. Even Transformers is more believable than this. I really hope Interstellar can make up for the bad taste this left. If someone rational could explain to me why this film is great, ie. Oscar-nod worthy, please do. I know you're going to say "allegory".

replies.commentText: 1. It is basically a Metaphor for our troubles in everyday Life and it is very deep and philosophical. 2. Something like this (a Space Movie in a realistic Style) was never done before, so it's pretty groundbreaking 3. For my opinion, the acting was really good, but i'm not an Expert 4. The Visuals were absoulutely gorgeus. You just felt like you really were in Space. (for example, when the ISS was hit, it looked just real and the aurora borealis looked really beautiful) 5. The Music was really fitting and also did its part to make you feel like you were in Space (good use of surround sound) 6. It had great cinematography (in the beginning there was a 13 Minute Scene WITHOUT ANY CUTS) As a Guy that has some knowledge about astrophysics, you'll obviously will notice all the inaccuracies, and it may ruin your expierience, try focusing on the accuracies and the Things this Movie did right, and you will propably enjoy it more.

Who cares about learning a lesson from a film? It's ENTERTAINMENT. Stop trying to read some stupid meaning into films and just enjoy them. For the first time ever I really believed this was happening in space and not some studio on wires. That's what makes it good. I believed it!

+xBloodyHeartx1 It taught those lessons in a terrible way. If you're mentally unstable like Dr. Stone is, you're not qualified to be an astronaut. Also, George letting go is so cliche I thought I was watching a shitty version of the Titanic. (I won't even mention the plot holes because you probably don't care much for plot.)

She isn't mentally unstable. She experienced a traumatic event in her past, and she continues to live her life in an affected manner (the driving). This represents that she is holding onto the past, technically moving, but not going anywhere. Hence not letting go. Anyway, this is her first time up in space, and when faced with uncertainty and death her anxieties come to the surface. Completely understandable in my opinion. As for not liking the George scene, I'll admit it wasn't completely original, but I was in a mindset to enjoy the movie, not loath every moment like you obviously were. And why on earth would you think I wasn't interested in the plot? We're debating; the plot is one of the most critical components.

+xBloodyHeartx1 Let me rephrase because you misinterpreted my point. Someone like Dr. Stone, who has so much emotional baggage, wouldn't be allowed on a flight to the ISS. For an average citizen who doesn't know what the requirements are to be an astronaut, Dr. Stone might seem like a possible candidate, but in reality this wouldn't happen. I was actually hooked to this movie the first few minutes, I'm a fan of astrophysics and I work in a hospital lab, like Dr. Stone. I tried to enjoy the movie. When they showed George messing around with his jet pack at the start, I thought to myself, "huh, I guess they have a huge supply of jet fuel for the pack". Then it turns out George dies because he runs out of fuel. Not to mention the fact that "leap frogging" from one space station to the next is absolutely ridiculous. It's one of those movies that forces the plot to keep the movie going.

Alright, I see your point, but I don't think she's just your average Joe. I think she was working with NASA (or what have you) before her daughter died. To be sent into space you have to be trained for years. So I think she is some sort of trained technician sent up to the Explorer to do some maintenance. Despite being terrified of being in space for the first time, she seemed fairly experienced with the hardware. Well, George was messing around since it was suppose to just be a quick space walk, but then he had to go after Stone and bring her to the station; I'm assuming hours have passed, so I don't think that is out of the question either. And what was so implausible about jumping around? They tried another space station, it had been evacuated due to the incoming threat, so they had to find alternative transportation.
the lesson is to "NEVER GIVE UP" idiot. she was going to let herself die, then she changed mind and survived. and thats particularly the lesson.

Spectacular argument. But no, I stand by my theory that the lesson is that sometimes you have to let go, and other times you have to hold on. Stone is pining over her dead daughter (she even explains that the reason she drives constantly is so that she doesn't have to face it) and she tried to save George even if it was hopeless. These are two events where she needs to let go, not "never give up." However, getting back to earth instead of letting herself die is symbolic to having to hold on.

+Minimalism HQ +xBloodyHeartx1 They the "never give up" lesson in a ridiculous way. She wouldn't be sent into space in the first place after her daughter died. NASA wouldn't let someone with so much emotional baggage on a mission critical trip. They should have come up with a better motivation to teach the "never give up" lesson. How do you even have to ask "what was so implausible about jumping around?" The space stations are not even located close to each other out in space, and their exact velocities are different as well. You don't just fly from one space station to another in an EVA suit. That's like travelling across the country in a wheel-chair with a limited supply of oxygen. How are some people so stupid? Are you like 12?

+Nikola JeliÄ‡ the fire extinguisher scene IS possible, several astronauts commented on it, it uses the same principles of physics as clooneys propulsion suit. and the movie said the capsule was designed specifically for landing, why else would it have a parachute? the comment your referring to is that this particular one WOULDNT work for re-entry because it was damaged, but it would work to get to the Chinese station which had one that worked. she also used the manual to over-ride the landing procedure and make it work in space. again the capsule is designed for re-entry, the reason it didn't burn up is because it had a heat shield, and again a parachute. this was actually the main tool astronauts used to get back to earth from space before the space shuttle.

+Nikola JeliÄ‡ I'm really not sure what part you're referring to in the movie where they claim that the Soyuz and Shenzhou can only go from spacecraft to spacecraft. All of the spacecraft portrayed in the movie are very closely based in appearance, function, and design on real-life spacecraft. The Soyuz and Shenzhou (a Chinese derivative of the Soyuz), are specifically designed to launch astronauts into orbit and bring them back safely to Earth in the return capsule. The depiction of Bullock's reentry and landing on Earth is similar to what an actual reentry and landing is like, down to the soft landing rockets that fire just prior to landing to decelerate the capsule. The soft landing rockets, which are again designed for landing, are actually pivotal to the movie's plot when Bullock uses them on the Soyuz to boost towards the Chinese Tiangong Space Station.

Astronauts are trained specifically to stay calm, even in the most extreme situations, so that instead of panicking like an average Joe, they use that energy to come up with a solution. The astronauts portrayed in "Gravity" couldn't possibly be further from the real deal.

replies.commentText: You can't train for a life or death situation. No one knows how they will truly react.

+Tony Fisher I have no reason to think that's true. Look into the kinds of tests and screenings astronauts go through. Many of them have even experienced extremely dangerous real life situations before ever going to space. Neil Armstrong was nearly killed during training for the Moon, when his Lunar Landing Research Vehicle (LLRV) broke down during flight. He was able to eject at the very last second. Armstrong expected his chances of surviving the first Moon landing to be 50/50. Many astronauts are previous test fliers of experimental aircraft, and perfectly able to think fast and stay useful in demanding situations. People who after endless testing and evaluations manage to be selected as astronauts, do not lose their heads when things get tough. If they did, they wouldn't be astronauts. Period.

commentText: Compared with what usually passes for "good" cinema these days, let alone Sci-fi, this film is pretty damn good. Having said that, it's also quite a strange mix of cliches, action spectacle, introspective drama and thriller elements. The action is indeed spectacular. And I think if Kubrick could've seen just how impressive the exterior space scenes look in this film, he might not have bothered with 2001: A Space Odyssey. He might have given up! The thriller elements are also very successful, in the way that there is really no antagonist in the film. Well, not unless you count space itself, of course. And there's a lot of excitement to be had with those damn oxygen tanks that always want to deplete at the worst possible moments. In fact, I think "Oxygen" might have been a better title for the film. Especially since the story has very little to do with gravity, and the crew's survival is utterly dependent on that precious O2. The dramatic part is where I thought the film felt a bit underwhelming. And this is in large part due to, what I consider, the miscasting of Sandra Bullock in the lead. No no, she's not bad in the part. But showing emotion is not her greatest strength, and emotion is ultimately what's supposed to drive this entire film. We, as the audience, are supposed to root for her. We're supposed to feel her frustration and anger, and empathize with her sense of hopelessness. And we're meant to share her progress and setbacks. In other words, we should be with her on her journey to safety and some sort of personal redemption. Unfortunately, that didn't happen for me. I found Sandra Bullock to be a little too stiff, and as a result, I didn't really relate enough to her to be fully engaged with the outcome. The way I see it, it could have been almost ANYONE in that space suit, since I had so little emotional investment with the character. No matter who would be trying to survive this ordeal, it would of course be exciting to watch, but without the emotional involvement, it doesn't feel like a great loss if the worst happens, and therefor, the film has (sort of) failed as a drama. I also didn't like the blatantly obvious religious overtones in the film. There are references everywhere. Even when we're in the Chinese space station, we're "treated" to a huge closeup of a Buddha statuette. Not to mention the return of "Angel George" at one crucial point. Or how Sandra, who's playing a doctor (a scientist), after admitting that she doesn't know how to pray because she never needed to, suddenly has a change of heart in the face of danger, and now "talks to God". I don't know, perhaps it's the Atheist in me that finds this hard to deal with. And the worst line of the film is: "Half of North America just lost their Facebook". SO? Facebook sucks! The loss of it would be good news! All in all, though, the film does avoid the worst of the usual space cliches. And when it doesn't, at least it weaves them into the story in a credible way, so that they don't distract us from what's important, unlike so many other films of this genre. And even though I've been bitching a bit about it, Gravity is by far the best Sci-fi film I've seen since Danny Boyle's Sunshine. Actually, Gravity is a much better film, and unlike Sunshine, it doesn't fuck up the ending. Worth watching, people!

What message would that be? Not that she landed on earth, not that she appreciated the dirty sand on the beach, I'm talking about the fact that the movie ended where it did, what message? And to those who say it said that a rescue team was deployer, I'm sorry, I must have missed that then. If that's the case the ending isn't as bad as I first thought, but I'd still appreciate an ending with more closure. They keep talking about "the incredible story" she gets to tell if she makes it back, but we NEVER get to see her tell that story. But each to his own, there is no blueprint for what is right and wrong here, I just stated my opinion, and my opinion is that I don't like "open endings" like this, it's the the entire movie builds up to the point where she is reunited with her child and society, and you never get to see it, it's a huge disappointment for me. I love endings like Inception that makes you think, that's fine, because it's an actual open ending that's puzzling and intelligent at the same time, endings like this is just a lazy attempt at making the movie artistic imo. Gravity is like Cast Away with an even worse ending, to me the movie builds up towards something you never get to see, it leaves me with an immense feeling of dissatisfaction. Again, my opinion, no need to get upset or label it as "wrong" just because your opinion differs from it (that goes to all the other comments here). Before I say anything else, I want to make it clear that Gravity is pretty unique, this is a singular and interesting movie Don't worry, I'm not going to make spoilers. I'll just point out some aspects that are explained at the very beginning of the movie and some other that doesn't have much importance in the plot, so don't worry, you can keep reading safely. That said, I don't appreciate AT ALL how Russians are portrayed, they seem stupid and incompetent in the movie. The idea of Russians disposing of satellites with missiles without having things under control is just absurd. I'm sick and tired of the obsolete Cold War drill of always blaming Russians for virtually anything, as if they were dumb, evil or something. Russia has been one of the most competent, prepared, talented and successful countries regarding space exploration. Hell, they were the first to launch a satellite, a dog and a man to outer space. They have been admirable pioneers of space travel since 1957. Now even American astronauts use the Russian Soyuz to get to the ISS, and they also learn Russian. If Russians were such fools, why the hell would Americans do this? It's easy, because Russians aren't fools, in fact they are pretty good at what they do. A couple of other things: 1- When you grab a moving object (like a ship) in outer space, you end up moving exactly at the same speed, direction, rotation, etc. as the object itself. It doesn't matter if you let go of it. As long as there's no pushing, pulling or acceleration, your movement and velocity will be exactly the same as that object's, you won't move away from it. If your ship is orbiting in space and you just let go of it, you'll keep your position relative to it for as long as neither of you accelerates. There's no moving away stuff, once you "get caught" by an object, you move exactly like it and your position relative to it is conserved. Pay atention to one particular scene with Clooney and you'll understand why I say this. 2- Astronauts in the movie move too fast through space in relation to the rest of moving objects. It almost seems like they are actually on Earth's atmosphere sometimes, judging by the speed of their movement relative to the other things. In space there's no such thing as moving fast in relation to your ship when it's already orbiting and you just let go of it or push/pull yourself a bit...not unless one of you starts accelerating a lot. Maybe the ship can do this by burning its engines, but astronauts definitely can't get much acceleration using just their own muscles. 3-If you have an rcs system then you don't need to use the main engine in order to make the ship move. The "Reaction Control System" allows ships to maneuver in space, you can easily recognize it by its typical small thrusters that release white fumes every time they are activated. They don't provide much thrust, but they can make the ship move in pretty much any direction at low speeds. 4-If you don't know Chinese and you have no experience with the ship... Well, you'll understand when you see the movie. I was going to say more, but I don't want to make spoilers, so I'll end here. Gravity is like a modern version of Apollo 13 with more special effects, more dramatization and much less realism.

Just saw "Gravity" and despite not living up to the incredible hype from the critics, it was a very good film. I would recommend that you make sure you see it in 3D at the Cinema (this coming from someone who hates 3D) as the 3-D in this film really does work and doesnt just have a 2D background with one part of the screen popping out at you. It immerses you fully into the film. Sure ive heard there are a few technical facts that are wrong and Cuaron admitted he knew about these but it was necessary for the sake of the medium of making a film. This isnt a NASA information video. The film is not on the same level in terms of 2001 Space Odyssey in terms of depth, its a far more visceral film that needs to be experienced in the cinema. Id also say the first half of the film is excellent and the second half is solid but not as good. There are still some metaphorical elements to the film revolving around sandra bullocks character and her reason for living or wanting to survive (I wont say any more as I will reveal spoilers.) Symbolism is included as well (fetal position and the end of the film etc)

commentText: Director Alfonso Cuaron summed up the film. I love this interpretation. "You have a character who's drifting into the void and is getting farther and farther away from human communication. It's a character that lives in her own bubble and is a victim of her own inertia. So it was a moment in which she has to come out of her own bubble and metaphorically shed her skin. She gets out of that suit and soon she's in her primordial state. The film deals with rebirth, and this is the first hint of that - the first moment that it's done visually in a more explicit way. This is a character who's been surrounded by death and, on the verge of it, finally finds peace and repose."

+Raphael MYT Point made. But I hope the maker figures a way out to explain this. :|

The vibration of air particles is the one that your ear receives, and your brain interpret that as sound. In space, there is no air, so nothing can vibrate, therefore, no sound, But, in case you touch something that is vibrating (for example, a piece of iron that just got hit by another one) the vibration is going to be transmitted to your body, and then the air inside your astronaut suit is going to catch something of that vibration, your ears are going to receive it and, therefore, you are going to hear something. Not the real sound that you would have on earth, but sound anyway. ONLY if you are touching something. Watch the trailer again, and notice how only the things that they touch are the ones that sound.

Actually, in the movie space IS mostly silent, except for music, the characters' voices, and anything else the character would realistically hear. The director actually said they added extra sound effects to the trailer to make it more "cinematic".

To the people knocking it for scientific inaccuracy: artistic license, ffs.

replies.commentText: +aigg Such as? Things like the distances involved are surely not an issue because they are used to heighten tension. I have seen even practicing scientists defend this movie from this kind of criticism. Prometheus is a great example of a movie ruined by the fact that it makes no internal sense, but within its own parameters Gravity does just fine.

+aigg " Others, however, such as Kevin Grazier, science adviser for the movie, and NASA engineer Robert Frost, maintain that the pair are actually still decelerating, with Stone's leg caught in the parachute cords from the Soyuz. As the cords absorb her kinetic energy, they stretch. Kowalski's interpretation of the situation is that the cords are not strong enough to absorb his kinetic energy as well as hers, and that he must therefore release the tether in order to give her a chance of stopping before the cords fail and doom both of them." She was attached to the chord by the smallest of margins. I think it was acceptable, and I'm afraid I find the 'scientific' criticisms of the movie to just be some nerdy OCD.
+aigg Oh, also: Buzz Aldrin praised it for accuracy. Case dismissed.

+aigg "all the science errors", to be honest some of those 'errors' are pathetic excuses to attack the film. "Aw, it would have been impossible to go from the sat to the ISS, lol" seriously if that is a big issue for people then good luck with Prometheus (which makes no sense even given its own rules of logic). You cannot say that their relative speed to the ISS is zero, they could still have been drifting slightly and it not have been apparent. Clooney's speed is zero relative to Stone, but perhaps they were both still drifting. Even if that is not exactly how it APPEARS on screen (even if the result of an error), it is still EASILY forgivable, other than by anally retentive science nerds. Scientists do not write good sci-fi, and I've read a fair bit of it (yes there are probably a few exceptions).
+aigg Also: Buzz Aldrin said it was remarkably faithful to the experience of being in space. Case closed.

A shot that alludes to this is when she comes back inside the air lock from almost losing consciousness (due to lack of O2) and wraps herself up like a baby while floating inside the air lock. A cord in the background of her resembles an umbilical cord, showing her "rebirth" from not giving up. From then on she encounters lots of tribulations but continues to live after having the desire to and accepting where she is. I study film producing and one crucial part of it is finding a film's theme.

The theme in this is moving on with life and finding your "middle path", which is a big practice in the Buddhist teachings. The fact that she learned this alone in space from her daughter's death, with no hospitality for life and no sound, shows just why she was able to come out of that alive. She was accepting of what happened and moved on from it, and in turn was given more opportunities in life.

Not to give myself more credit, but I am currently studying producing at film school and one of the most crucial elements is picking out a theme in a film.

While an IMAX screens are important, few people seem to mention sound setups. This sound for Gravity was designed for Dolby ATMOS. Instead of a series of surround sound speakers one a single plane, ATMOS uses an array of speakers on the walls and ceiling. This allows for the an unbelievable aural perception of depth and scale, as the perceived origin point of sounds are moving around in three dimensions instead of two. You can search for theaters with Dolby ATMOS on Dolby's website.

To educate your dumb ass further, the force of gravity in LEO (low Earth orbit) is almost as strong as it is on the surface of the Earth. An object in any orbit around the Earth stays in orbit because it is moving laterally at a very high speed, and this velocity offsets the effect of gravity. If the object slows down, it immediately begins falling to Earth under the force of gravity. That's precisely how an orbiting spacecraft re-enters the atmosphere and returns to Earth, by slowing down.

Not to be all sheldon cooper about it but, G ("big G") is unit-less. It's the gravitational constant. However, "g" (ie "little g") is the unit of acceleration you mentioned before. Little "g" is specific for earth's gravity. Little "g" is equal to (G times Mass of the Earth) divided by R^2. Just saying if you're going to correct somebody, helps to be correct yourself.

Wrong. Her body is also subject to centrifugal force generated by the rotation of the arm. This force is directed outward from the center of rotation, and would work to propel her in that direction the moment she detaches. Her actual trajectory would be the resultant of that vector and the translational (straight line) motion vector, so it would depend on when exactly she detached.

The implausibility is much greater than that. It's a 3D issue, not a 2D one. Orbital paths also vary in their distance from (height above) the Earth. The Hubble telescope is in a much higher orbit than that of the space station. Orbiting debris impacting Hubble would thus remain far away from anything orbiting at the height of the space station. And it would be equally impossible for an astronaut orbiting at/near Hubble height to descend to space station height without the use of a spacecraft.

Astronaut training prepares them to perform their assigned tasks and to trouble shoot problems that may occur in and on the exterior of the spacecraft, or perhaps on a satellite they will be working on. Nothing in their training prepares them for being flung away from the spacecraft untethered and beyond any hope of rescue, unless it has to do with the use of a cyanide capsule or something like that.

The fear has nothing to do with the size of the universe and everything to do with running out of oxygen long before anyone can reach you much less rescue you. Also, she's not drifting into "pitch black". She's drifting into a slightly higher but still very low Earth orbit... to her the Earth will look just as huge and bright as it did back where the shuttle was destroyed.

Furthermore, not all astronauts are created equal when it comes to "the Right Stuff". Most shuttle and ISS era astronauts are NOT the classic Type-A fighter pilot with nerves of steel variety, as all of the Mercury, Gemini and Apollo astronauts were. When Neil Armstrong had to improvise the landing of the Apollo 11 lunar module with only seconds of fuel left, he remained calm. Most any latter-day mission specialist would have shit his/her pants in that situation.

Google "Kessler Syndrome" it's the situation this movie is based off of. Basically, when something is on a very fast orbit, and it collides with something else, it has the potential to create even more debris which follows in the same orbit, causing a domino effect. Let me see if I can mangle the answer. As you know, sound is the vibration from the explosion, etc., traveling as a wave in a medium. Sound is mechanical energy, and anything that exhibits movement can make sound. But the sound has to have something to travel in. A gas or a liquid or a solid is a medium, and the sound will travel in them (or will be conducted through them). No air, no medium, no sound.

The Earth's atmosphere doesn't just stop at a certain distance from the Earth, it kind of fades away. The Earth's thermosphere starts at about 59 miles up, and ends roughly 420 miles up, it still contains molecules just very spread out. It's better to not think of them as actual layers, but a thinning as you go higher. The Earth's atmosphere doesn't really "end" it just gets fewer molecules the further you go up, and that distance is about ~10,000km (~6200 miles) up.
